    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2095922155" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2095922155" />
    <a title="Bbrown" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6261192-bbrown"><img alt="Bbrown" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404741580p2/6261192.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2095922155?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bbrown" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bbrown" href="/user/show/6261192-bbrown">Bbrown</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6261192-bbrown?shelf=horror">horror</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2095922155" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14293299019167301491">I found Tales of Moonlight and Rain because I had begun reading Lafcadio Hearn’s Kwaidan and been struck by how westernized the supernatural folktales were, which led me to seek out a more authentic collection of such Japanese tales. Tales of Moonlight and Rain is certainly more authentic than Kwaidan, as Chambers has put obvious effort into translating these stories so as to keep them as close to the original text as possible, but unfortunately a good deal of the entertainment value of these st</span>
  <span id="freeText14293299019167301491" style="display:none">I found Tales of Moonlight and Rain because I had begun reading Lafcadio Hearn’s Kwaidan and been struck by how westernized the supernatural folktales were, which led me to seek out a more authentic collection of such Japanese tales. Tales of Moonlight and Rain is certainly more authentic than Kwaidan, as Chambers has put obvious effort into translating these stories so as to keep them as close to the original text as possible, but unfortunately a good deal of the entertainment value of these stories had to be sacrificed on the altar of academic understanding. <br /><br />Perhaps the key thing to know about Tales of Moonlight and Rain before picking it up is that this is primarily an academic text. It is very well sourced, and Chambers is obviously an expert through-and-through on this subject matter, but this collection is in essence a mini-textbook. Every story is preceded by several pages giving historical context and analysis of potential influences on the tale, and every story is followed by several pages of endnotes on the text, which are in addition to the footnotes that appear during the story itself. With annotations on all sides, the tales themselves are smothered, their flow constantly interrupted and never able to breathe. While Hearn’s Kwaidan is primarily concerned with telling entertaining stories, Chambers’s Tales of Moonlight and Rain is primarily concerned with getting you to understand these tales and their significance. Neither focus is inherently superior to the other, but I went into this collection hoping to find some entertaining stories, and was therefore a bit disappointed. <br /><br />This disappointment was magnified a bit by what the collection actually contained: multiple tales aren’t primarily about strange occurrences, as the title of the collection suggests, but are merely using a strange occurrence as a framing narrative to discuss other matters. This is best exemplified by the first tale in the collection, Shiramine, where an encounter with a ghost is used to have a Buddhist/Confucian dialogue and history lesson, and the last tale in the collection, On Poverty and Wealth, which is (surprise, surprise) primarily a dialogue on poverty and wealth. Again, from an academic standpoint, these are both potentially fascinating, but as stories they leave something to be desired.<br /><br />As an educational text, Tales of Moonlight and Rain seems fine, but the academic focus of the Chambers edition undermines it as a work of literature. It is certainly more authentic than Kwaidan, but I think that a more successful balance between authenticity and entertainment was struck by Strange Tales from a Chinese Studio by Pu Songling, which I recommend to you if you liked Tales of Moonlight and Rain, so long as your interest in supernatural folktales extends beyond Japan.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14293299019167301491" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

