        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer596666360" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12671235534032952560">It might be a 20th (wait, we&apos;re in the 21st now aren&apos;t we?) century lens looking at these tales, but though they were mighty interesting tales, the climaxes felt too soon, the story too elaborated. I feel like maybe I was just expecting a twist ending to come last minute. Again, 21st century.<br/>But they are richly interesting tales, if you are into eastern culture. Very strong references to Chinese literature and history, but really this is pretty much the equivalent of English literature evoking t</span>
  <span id="freeText12671235534032952560" style="display:none">It might be a 20th (wait, we're in the 21st now aren't we?) century lens looking at these tales, but though they were mighty interesting tales, the climaxes felt too soon, the story too elaborated. I feel like maybe I was just expecting a twist ending to come last minute. Again, 21st century.<br />But they are richly interesting tales, if you are into eastern culture. Very strong references to Chinese literature and history, but really this is pretty much the equivalent of English literature evoking the Greeks.<br />The title (original Japanese being almost identical) really hits on the head the atmosphere of these stories. Maybe it's even best to read it on a moonlit, but lightly rainy evening. If that contradiction even can make sense.<br />Also. Everything is being blamed on foxes (kitsune), but I just want to get this one thing straight: In not a single tale was a single fox, or fox-succubus to blame for a single character's misfortunes or discomforts. Oni yes, kitsune no. The one where the actual Spirit of Money comes out to chat one was downright odd.<br /><br />The first two tales [and a few bits of others] were mixed together to form the absolutely fascinating 1953 movie of the same name (雨月物語 - <i>Ugetsu Monogatari</i>, or simply <i>Ugestu</i>) by Kenji Mizoguchi, essentially considered by some to be the greatest film Japan every produced. I really enjoyed the film and suggest fans of the book watch the film and visa versa.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12671235534032952560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


